#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:550
msgid "Custom weekmasks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:552
msgid ""
"Here are several examples of custom weekmask values.  These examples specify "
"the \"busday\" default of Monday through Friday being valid days."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:555
msgid "Some examples::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:557
msgid ""
"# Positional sequences; positions are Monday through Sunday.\n"
"# Length of the sequence must be exactly 7.\n"
"weekmask = [1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0]\n"
"# list or other sequence; 0 == invalid day, 1 == valid day\n"
"weekmask = \"1111100\"\n"
"# string '0' == invalid day, '1' == valid day\n"
"\n"
"# string abbreviations from this list: Mon Tue Wed Thu Fri Sat Sun\n"
"weekmask = \"Mon Tue Wed Thu Fri\"\n"
"# any amount of whitespace is allowed; abbreviations are case-sensitive.\n"
"weekmask = \"MonTue Wed  Thu\\tFri\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:573
msgid "Datetime64 shortcomings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:575
msgid ""
"The assumption that all days are exactly 86400 seconds long makes "
"`datetime64` largely compatible with Python `datetime` and \"POSIX time\" "
"semantics; therefore they all share the same well known shortcomings with "
"respect to the UTC timescale and historical time determination. A brief non "
"exhaustive summary is given below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:581
msgid ""
"It is impossible to parse valid UTC timestamps occurring during a positive "
"leap second."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:586
msgid ""
"\"2016-12-31 23:59:60 UTC\" was a leap second, therefore \"2016-12-31 "
"23:59:60.450 UTC\" is a valid timestamp which is not parseable by "
"`datetime64`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:599
msgid ""
"Timedelta64 computations between two UTC dates can be wrong by an integer "
"number of SI seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:604
msgid ""
"Compute the number of SI seconds between \"2021-01-01 12:56:23.423 UTC\" and "
"\"2001-01-01 00:00:00.000 UTC\":"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:617
msgid ""
"However, the correct answer is `631198588.423` SI seconds, because there "
"were 5 leap seconds between 2001 and 2021."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:620
msgid ""
"Timedelta64 computations for dates in the past do not return SI seconds, as "
"one would expect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:625
msgid ""
"Compute the number of seconds between \"000-01-01 UT\" and \"1600-01-01 "
"UT\", where UT is `universal time <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Universal_Time>`_:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:638
msgid ""
"The computed results, `50491123200` seconds, are obtained as the elapsed "
"number of days (`584388`) times `86400` seconds; this is the number of "
"seconds of a clock in sync with the Earth's rotation. The exact value in SI "
"seconds can only be estimated, e.g., using data published in `Measurement of "
"the Earth's rotation: 720 BC to AD 2015, 2016, Royal Society's Proceedings A "
"472, by Stephenson et.al. <https://doi.org/10.1098/rspa.2016.0404>`_. A "
"sensible estimate is `50491112870 ± 90` seconds, with a difference of 10330 "
"seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:651
msgid "Migration guide for deprecation of generic units"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:653
msgid ""
"The generic units of `timedelta64` are deprecated since NumPy 2.5 and will "
"raise an error in the future. This section provides guidance on how to "
"update code that uses generic units of `timedelta64` to avoid future errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:658
msgid ""
"The straight forward way is to replace the generic unit with a specific time "
"unit such as 'D' (day), 'h' (hour), 'm' (minute), 's' (second), etc. The "
"choice of the specific time unit will depend on the context of your code and "
"the level of precision you require."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:676
msgid ""
"When comparing `timedelta64` objects, make sure to use the same specific "
"time unit for both operands even if they are representing ``0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.datetime.rst:685
msgid ""
"When using ``numpy.testing.assert_allclose`` to compare `timedelta64` "
"objects, ensure to set a specific time unit to ``atol`` parameter as well."
msgstr ""
